"Following closely upon the publication of the Consultative Memorandum (see [1988–1989] 4 CLSR 20–22), the Law Commssion for England and Wales has produced another assessment of the effectiveness of existing criminal law to deal with what they prefer to call “computer misuse”. There is no doubt that this is an important document for all of us and is almost certain to form the basis for any impending changes to sunstantive criminal law. For those readers who have particular concern with the impact of the criminal law in this area there can be no substitute for purchasing are reading the Working Paper (Law Commission Working Paper No. 110, Computer Misuse, HMSO, £4.50). What follows is a summary of the Commission's main arguments and provisional conclusions, together with some critical comment. It should be emphasised that the Working Paper is a consultation document and in a number of important areas the Commission's views are not yet settled. They are anxious to receive comment on their proposals from those individuals and groups who have working knowledge of the technical aspects of the subject, who may be ab;e to envisage potential risks which have not been unearthed by the Commission. Any such comments should be received by the Law Commission by the end of February 1989."
